{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565739"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:31:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18445"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.05,0.09,0.12,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11163"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90308"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11163"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74562"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1004"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3728"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"8932"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25877"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30630"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90308"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing fatigue, night sweats, and unexplained bruising. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has worked as a petroleum refinery operator for the past 25 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears pale. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 118/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has scattered bruises on his arms and legs. There is no lymphadenopathy or hepatosplenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin 85 g/L (130-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ewhite cell count 32 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eplatelets 45 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eblood film shows numerous myeloblasts with Auer rods (\u0026gt;20%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following occupational exposures is most likely to have contributed to this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benzene","Silica particles","Mercury vapour","Lead dust","Asbestos fibres"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and laboratory findings consistent with acute myeloid leukaemia (AML). The combination of cytopenias, numerous myeloblasts on blood film, and constitutional symptoms in the context of occupational exposure to petroleum products strongly suggests benzene-induced AML.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzene\u003C/strong\u003E is a known carcinogen with a well-established association with AML. It is commonly found in petroleum products and industrial solvents. Long-term exposure, even at relatively low levels, can lead to bone marrow toxicity and subsequent development of leukaemia. The latency period between exposure and disease development can be several years to decades.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsbestos fibres\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily associated with mesothelioma and lung cancer, not haematological malignancies. Exposure typically occurs in construction, shipbuilding, and insulation work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELead dust\u003C/strong\u003E exposure can cause anaemia through interference with haem synthesis, but it is not associated with leukaemia. Symptoms of lead toxicity include abdominal pain, constipation, and neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMercury vapour\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the central nervous system and kidneys. It is not known to cause haematological malignancies. Exposure typically occurs in mining, dental work, and certain manufacturing processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESilica particles\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with silicosis and increased risk of lung cancer, but not with haematological malignancies. Exposure typically occurs in mining, construction, and sandblasting operations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of benzene-related leukaemia relies on proper workplace controls including ventilation systems, personal protective equipment, and regular monitoring of exposure levels. Regular medical surveillance of workers exposed to benzene is also important for early detection of any haematological abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Benzene exposure is a known risk factor for developing acute myeloid leukaemia.","Occupational history is crucial in identifying potential carcinogenic exposures.","Personal protective equipment and workplace controls are essential in preventing exposure to benzene and other carcinogens."],"references":["Smith MT, Jones RM, Smith AH. Benzene exposure and risk of leukemia. Lancet. 2007;370(9592):1603-1615 Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(07)61691-5","Snyder R. Benzene and leukemia. Crit Rev Toxicol. 2002;32(3):155-210 Available at: https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/20024091064133","International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC). Benzene. IARC Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. 2018;120:249-260 Available at: https://publications.iarc.fr/586"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74562"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74562"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T17:19:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T17:24:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11163"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic